{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526417"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14133"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14133"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.07,0.09,0.64,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55830"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6813"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41376"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6251"},{"type":"tags","id":"6252"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43493"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55830"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about lumps on her hands that have been present for several months. She reports difficulty performing her work as a secretary. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are firm, non-tender subcutaneous nodules over the proximal interphalangeal joints of both hands (Image). Similar nodules are noted on her elbows.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is NOT an extra-articular manifestation associated with this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interstitial lung disease","Episcleritis","Mesangioproliferative glomerulonephritis","Acute myeloid leukaemia","Accelerated atherosclerosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with rheumatoid nodules, which are a common extra-articular manifestation of rheumatoid arthritis (RA). The stem describes firm, subcutaneous nodules over the proximal interphalangeal joints and elbows, which are typical locations for rheumatoid nodules. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute myeloid leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically considered an extra-articular manifestation of RA. While patients with RA may have a slightly increased risk of certain malignancies, including lymphoma, AML is not specifically associated with RA. From a haematology perspective, many patients with RA have anaemia of chronic disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterstitial lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-recognized extra-articular manifestation of RA. It can occur in up to 10% of RA patients and is associated with increased morbidity and mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiscleritis\u003C/strong\u003E is an ocular manifestation of RA. It presents as acute redness of the eye and is usually self-limiting. More severe ocular manifestations like scleritis can also occur in RA patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesangioproliferative glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a renal manifestation that can occur in RA. Renal involvement in RA can take various forms, including glomerulonephritis, amyloidosis, and vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccelerated atherosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is an important extra-articular manifestation of RA. Patients with RA have an increased risk of cardiovascular disease, partly due to chronic inflammation promoting atherosclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther extra-articular manifestations of RA include vasculitis, pericarditis, pleuritis, and secondary Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome. The presence of extra-articular manifestations often indicates more severe disease and may require more aggressive treatment. Regular monitoring for these complications is an important part of RA management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rheumatoid nodules are usually found over pressure points or extensor surfaces, particularly on the hands, elbows, and feet.","The presence of rheumatoid nodules is associated with a more aggressive disease course and increased risk of cardiovascular complications."],"references":["Cojocaru M, Cojocaru IM, Silosi I, Vrabie CD, Tanasescu R. Extra-articular Manifestations in Rheumatoid Arthritis. Maedica. 2010;5(4):286\u201391. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3152850/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41376"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14133"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21009"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21009"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DfN18X97GZo3UU09ciCuazBVnAiuiY.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DfN18X97GZo3UU09ciCuazBVnAiuiY.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41376"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:47:17+10:30